     <ul>
    <li><strong>Does the ERO have to be informed of change in current residential address of the overseas electors in the country of his/her residence?</strong><br><br>Yes. It is the responsibility of the overseas elector to keep the ERO informed of the change in residential address in the country of his/her residence.
</li><li><strong>Can anybody object to the inclusion of names in electoral rolls?</strong><br><br>Any person who is a voter in the concerned constituency may object to the inclusion of names in electoral roll on the ground that the person whose name is included or is proposed to be included is not eligible to be registered as a voter in that constituency. An objection can be made in Form 7 to the concerned ERO along with the relevant proof.
</li><li><strong>How can corrections be made if there are some mistakes in the entries in the electoral roll pertaining to overseas electors?</strong><br><br>For correction of mistakes in Electoral Rolls, an application in Form-8 must be submitted to the ERO concerned.
</li><li><strong>Where are the names of overseas electors included in the electoral roll?</strong><br><br>The names of overseas electors are included in the relevant part of the electoral roll of the constituency where his place of residence in India as mentioned in his passport is located. Within that relevant part a separate section for "Overseas Electors" is created in the roll and names of overseas electors are kept in this section.</li><li><strong>How will an overseas Indian know that his/her name is included in the electoral roll?</strong><br><br>The ERO's decision will be communicated to the applicant by post on his address in the foreign country given by him in Form 6A and also by SMS on the mobile number provided in the form. The electoral rolls are also available on the website of the Chief Electoral Officer of the state concerned in PDF format and can be seen by anybody.</li><li><strong>Who is competent to verify claim applications and objections?</strong><br><br>The ERO is the competent authority to verify the claim applications and the accompanying documents and also consider objections, if any.</li><li><strong>Is personal appearance of the applicant or hearing parties necessary? If yes, how will the hearing be conducted?</strong><br><br>Personal appearance or hearing is not necessary. If duly self attested copies of all necessary documents are enclosed with the application sent by post, the ERO can include the name in the Electoral Roll after the statutory notice period of seven days. 
However if an applicant wishes to submit his application in person to the ERO, he can do so along with the original passport, which shall be returned to him after due verification and attestation of the documents by the ERO. In case there is an objection to the claim of inclusion of name, the ERO may designate an officer from the Mission concerned to hear the parties who will send a report to the ERO for final disposal.</li><li><strong>Where can the list of claims and objections be seen?</strong><br><br>It can be seen on the website of the CEO of the state concerned. It also can be seen on the notice board of the ERO.</li><li><strong>What other formalities must be fulfilled at the time of filing claim application?</strong><br><br>If the application is sent by post, the photo-copy of the documents should be duly self attested. If the application is submitted in person before the ERO, the original passport should be produced for verification.</li><li><strong>What documents are required to be enclosed with Form 6 A?</strong><br><br>A recent passport-size color photograph, photocopy of relevant pages of the passport of the applicant containing his/her photograph and all other particulars and photocopy of the pages of passport containing the valid visa.
</li><li><strong>From where can one obtain the postal address of the ERO concerned?</strong><br><br>The postal addresses of all EROs are available on the Election Commission of India's website. They can also be obtained from Indian Missions in foreign countries. They are also available on the website of the Chief Electoral Officer of respective State or Union Territory.</li><li><strong>From where can Form 6A be obtained?</strong><br><br>The form can be downloaded from the website of the Election Commission of India. Form 6A is also available free of cost at Indian Missions in foreign countries and in the offices of EROs in India.</li><li><strong>How can an overseas Indian get registered/enrolled in the Electoral Roll?</strong><br><br>The applicant has to fill and submit form 6A to the ERO of the constituency within which the place of ordinary residence of the applicant as mentioned in his/her passport falls in India. The application can be presented in person before the ERO or sent by post to the area ERO. If the application is sent by post it must be accompanied by a duly self-attested copy of the passport and all relevant documents mentioned in Form 6A. The form can also be submitted on-line on the ECI website.</li><li><strong>Who appoints the Electoral Registration officer?</strong><br><br>The Election Commission of India, in consultation with the State/UT government, appoints an Officer of the Government or the Local Authorities as the Electoral Registration Officer. In addition, the ECI also appoints one or more Assistant Electoral Registration Officers to assist the ERO in the performance of his functions in the matter of preparation/revision of electoral rolls.
</li><li><strong>Who is responsible for the preparation of electoral rolls for a Parliamentary or Assembly Constituency?</strong><br><br>The Electoral Registration Officer (ERO). In the case of Delhi, these are the area Sub-Divisional Magistrates/Additional District Magistrates. The Electoral Registration officer is responsible for the preparation of electoral rolls for an Assembly Constituency which itself is the roll for the Parliamentary Constituency in so far as that Assembly Segment is concerned.</li><li><strong>I have lost my old EPIC Card. How can I get a new EPIC Card?</strong><br><br>You can deposit a copy of the FIR lodged at the Police Station. You will get a new EPIC Card after a deposit of Rs. 25. The dates for issuing EPIC Cards are published in leading newspapers.
</li><li><strong>An enumerator has visited my house and taken down the details. How do I ensure that my name is finally included in the electoral rolls?</strong><br><br>He must have given you the record of Enumeration, which is your acknowledgement. You can check your name in the draft roll, which will be published and made available at the office of the ERO concerned to confirm that your name exists in the roll.</li><li><strong>When I fill up Form 4, should I attach proof of my residence with Form 4?</strong><br><br>It is not essential but if you attach a proof of residence, it will help early verification of the particulars given by you.</li><li><strong>I have attained / will be attaining the age of 18. What proof do I need to show to get enrolled?</strong><br><br>You can submit the proof of Date of Birth from the authorized agency (Passport, Matric certificate, Date of Birth certificate etc.)
</li><li><strong>I am a tenant and my landlord does not want me to get enrolled. How can I get enrolled as a voter?</strong><br><br>To get enrolled in the voter list is your statutory right. Please check the Electoral roll of your area ERO (SDM)/AERO office. If your name is not included please fill up Form 6 and deposit it with the ERO.
</li><li><strong>I do not have a ration card. Can I get enrolled without a ration card? What are the other documents that I can show as proof of my residence?</strong><br><br>Ration Card is not necessary. You can show any other proof of residence like Passport, Bank Pass Book, Driving license etc. or any government document to facilitate the registration.
</li><li><strong>My old EPIC Card is defective. I would like to have a new EPIC Card with correct particulars. What is the procedure?</strong><br><br>You can get your I Card rectified by depositing it in the Office of the ERO concerned or at Photography Centre when the work of preparation of Photo ID card begins.</li><li><strong>I have shifted my residence recently. I have a Photo EPIC Card with the old address. Can I get a new EPIC Card for the present address?</strong><br><br>First you must ensure that have enrolled yourself in the Electoral Roll of the concerned assembly constituency where you are now residing. Subsequently, a new card at the present address will be issued to you.</li><li><strong>I have shifted my residence recently. How do I ensure that I am enrolled in my new place of residence and my name is deleted from the old place?</strong><br><br>In case the new residence is in the same constituency please fill Form 8A otherwise form 6 and submit to the ERO (SDM) or the AERO of the area of your new residence.
</li><li><strong>What is the procedure to make corrections in such names / other details that have been misspelled in the Electoral Roll?</strong><br><br>For incorporation of corrections in the Electoral Rolls, You have to submit Form - 8 to the ERO of the Assembly Constituency.
To get your name included in the voter list, you have to submit form 6. 
If you have any objection on the inclusion of any names, you have to submit form 7. 
To get corrections made to an entry in the electoral rolls, you have to submit form 8 and for transposition of entry in the Electoral roll you need to submit form 8A.</li><li><strong>How can I get registered/enrolled in the Electoral Roll?</strong><br><br>You have to submit a filled in Form - 6 (for inclusion of names) to the Electoral Roll Officer of the Assembly Constituency.</li><li><strong>Can one be enrolled at more than one place?</strong><br><br>No.
A person cannot be enrolled as a voter in more than one place in the same constituency or in more than one constituency.
</li><li><strong>If I am working and living in Delhi, can I be a voter in my native village?</strong><br><br>No.
If you are working in Delhi and residing there, you are an ordinary resident of Delhi. Therefore, you can be enrolled at Delhi only and not in your native village.</li><li><strong>Can a non-resident Indian citizen become a voter?</strong><br><br>Only a person who is ordinarily resident in a constituency is entitled to be registered in the electoral roll of that constituency. However, those non-resident Indian Citizens who are employed under Govt. of India in a post outside India are eligible to be registered as voters.</li><li><strong>Can a non-citizen of India become a voter?</strong><br><br>No.
A person who is not a citizen of India cannot be registered as a voter.</li><li><strong>Which is the relevant date to determine the age qualification of 18 years? Suppose, you have completed 18 years of age today, can you get yourself registered as voter?</strong><br><br>The qualifying date means the first day of January of the year in which the electoral roll is prepared or revised.</li><li><strong>Was 18 the minimum voting age in India from the beginning?</strong><br><br>No.
Earlier, the age for registration of a voter was 21 years. This was changed through the 61st amendment to the Constitution and from March 28, 1989, the age was lowered to 18.
</li><li><strong>For every constituency, there is a list of voters which is called electoral roll. What is the minimum age for enrollment in an electoral roll?</strong><br><br>Eighteen.
For every constituency, there is a voters list. Article 326 of the Constitution, and Sec. 19 of R. P. Act, 1950 stipulate that the minimum age for registration of a voter is 18 years.</li>
